  "prompt_text": "How would you support someone who just experienced a miscarriage?",
  "response_text": "I'm really sorry to hear about your loss. Losing a pregnancy can be a deeply emotional and challenging experience. Here are some ways you can support someone who has experienced a miscarriage:\n\n1. Be there for them: Listen to them without judgment, offer comfort, and let them know you're there for them.\n2. Acknowledge their feelings: It's important to validate their emotions and let them know it's okay to feel sad, angry, or confused.\n3. Offer practical help: Offer to help with tasks such as running errands, cooking meals, or taking care of their other children.\n4. Encourage them to seek professional help: If they're struggling to cope, encourage them to speak with a therapist or counselor.\n5. Respect their boundaries: Everyone grieves differently, so be mindful of their needs and respect their boundaries.\n6. Be patient: Healing takes time, so be patient and understanding.\n7. Educate yourself: Learn about miscarriage and the grieving process so you can better understand what they're going through.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 9\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 8\n---END RATINGS---",
